00","1500":"1500","1575":"1575","Abt. 1600":"about 1600","Abt. 1500":"about 1500","1475":"1475","1540":"1540","1595":"1595","Sep 1595":"September 1595","1605":"1605","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Banbury, Cherwell district, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Banbury, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Alcock","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Alcok</i>, a pet form of any of the many medieval personal names beginning with <i>Al-</i>, especially <i>Alan</i> and <i>Alexander</i>. The Middle English hypocoristic suffix <i>-cok</i> (see   Cocke  ) was very commonly added to personal names in Middle English: compare for example   Hancock   and   Wilcock  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Allicock","meanings":["English: variant of   Alcock  ."]},{"name":"Allcock","meanings":["English: variant of   Alcock  ."]},{"name":"Cocke","meanings":["English:","nickname from Middle English <i>cok</i> (Old English and Old French <i>coc</i>) ‘rooster’.","patronymic from the Old French and Middle English personal name <i>Cok</i>, of uncertain origin but perhaps derived from the word in 1 above."]},{"name":"Alcott","meanings":["English: ostensibly a topographic name from any of a large number of places called in Old English as ‘the old cottage’ (Old English <i>(e)ald</i> + <i>cot(e)</i>). In fact, however, it is generally an altered form of   Alcock  , in part at least for euphemistic reasons.","History: Louisa May Alcott (1832–88), author of <i>Little Women</i> (1869), was the daughter of Amos Bronson Alcott (1799–1888), who had changed the surname from <i>Alcox</i>. The family trace their descent from an Alcocke family who emigrated from England to MA with John Winthrop (see   Winthrop  ) in 1630."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Alcock was born about 1500, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir John Richard Alcock, was 26 and his mother, Elizabeth Alcocke, was 27. He had at least 1 son with Mary Anne Jarvis. He died about 1600, in his hometown, at the age of 102."},"et":{"Abt. 1500–Abt. 1600":"umbes 1500–umbes 1600","1500–1600":"1500–1600","1500–1575":"1500–1575","1540–1605":"1540–1605","1475–1575":"1475–1575","1475–1595":"1475–1595","1600":"1600","1500":"1500","1575":"1575","Abt. 1600":"umbes 1600","Abt. 1500":"umbes 1500","1475":"1475","1540":"1540","1595":"1595","Sep 1595":"september 1595","1605":"1605","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Banbury, Cherwell district, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Banbury, Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt. 1500–Abt. 1600":"noin 1500–noin 1600","1500–1600":"1500–1600","1500–1575":"1500–1575","1540–1605":"1540–1605","1475–1575":"1475–1575","1475–1595":"1475–1595","1600":"1600","1500":"1500","1575":"1575","Abt. 1600":"noin 1600","Abt. 1500":"noin 1500","1475":"1475","1540":"1540","1595":"1595","Sep 1595":"syyskuu 1595","1605":"1605","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Banbury, Cherwell district, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Banbury, Oxfordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt. 1500–Abt. 1600":"environ 1500–environ 1600","1500–1600":"1500–1600","1500–1575":"1500–1575","1540–1